# Preparing data

# I think we want to keep all of these variables but the name
clusterData=data[,c(2:13)]

#save the country names as the row index
row.names(clusterData)=data$name

clusterData
# computing distance matrix

set.seed(999)
library(cluster)
Warning: package cluster was built under R version 4.2.2
distanceMatrix=daisy(x=clusterData, metric = "gower")
projectedData = cmdscale(distanceMatrix, k=2)
# save coordinates to original data frame:
data$dim1 = projectedData[,1]
data$dim2 = projectedData[,2]

# see some:

data[,c('dim1','dim2')][1:10,]
library(ggplot2)
Warning: package ggplot2 was built under R version 4.2.2
base= ggplot(data=data,
             aes(x=dim1, y=dim2,
                 label=name)) 
base + geom_text(size=2)

# prepare hierarchical cluster
hc = hclust(distanceMatrix)
# very simple dendrogram
plot(hc,hang = -1,cex=0.5)

# Computing clusters
library(factoextra)
Warning: package factoextra was built under R version 4.2.2Welcome! Want to learn more? See two factoextra-related books at https://goo.gl/ve3WBa
# Hierarchical (agglomerative) method:

fviz_nbclust(clusterData, 
             hcut,
             diss=distanceMatrix,
             method = "gap_stat",
             k.max = 10,
             verbose = F,
             hc_func = "agnes")

# Hierarchical (divisive) method:
fviz_nbclust(clusterData, 
             hcut,
             diss=distanceMatrix,
             method = "gap_stat",
             k.max = 10,
             verbose = F,
             hc_func = "diana")

  1. Computing Clusters
# Computing clusters:

NumberDesiredClusters=1 #both methods had 1 as optimal no. of clusters
# this doesn't even mean anything

# Hierarchical - agglom:
res.agnes= hcut(distanceMatrix, 
                k = NumberDesiredClusters,
                isdiss=TRUE,
                hc_func='agnes',
                hc_method = "ward.D2")

# Hierarchical - divisive:
res.diana= hcut(distanceMatrix, 
                k = NumberDesiredClusters,
                isdiss=TRUE,
                hc_func='diana',
                hc_method = "ward.D2")
  1. Results from Clustering
# Results from Clustering

# Saving results to original dataframe
data$agn=as.factor(res.agnes$cluster)
data$dia=as.factor(res.diana$cluster)
# verify ordinality in clusters

diaEval=data.frame(res.diana$silinfo$widths)

agnPoor=rownames(agnEval[agnEval$sil_width<0,])
diaPoor=rownames(diaEval[diaEval$sil_width<0,])

We fail to find any meaningful results from the clustering data because it grouped all the countries into one cluster. Lets try a factor analysis of the same country-level data.

We end up with three factors: MR1 has child mortality rate, total fertility rate, education expeditures (negatively correlated) and energy consumption per capita (negatively correlated) as components, MR2 has net migration rate and inflation rate as components, and MR3 has unemployment rate and gini coefficent as components. I hypothesize that MR1 represents the latent concept of a countrys development level as I expect chid mortality rate and total fertility rate to be positively correlated with development level and education expenditures and energy consumption to be negatively correlated with a countrys development level. I hypothesize that MR3 represents a countrys inequality, as that factor is positively correlated with the Gini coefficient and unemployment rate. This is a stretch but I hypothesize MR2 to represent scarcity, as scarcity is positively correlated with inflation rate and migration rate. It should be noted though, that with an MSA of 0.61, the factor scores are likely not completely accurate.
